{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_black_ver02/data/sn84020751/00415667899/1908021301/0617.xml":{"full_text":"J\nNEWS FROM WALTER.\nInterestino News Items From\nthat Frospereus\nNeighborhood\ni .1 1\nBsgmTtsar'aff'.MB' \"\"\"if -a amroji'fcg,tl3 rv y SS yh xSfc,\nI\nAKGTJS BUREAU.\nWALTER, N. C\nFeb. 11, 1907.\nMrs. Lou Dai, who has been quite\nsik with grip for the past week, is\ninr; proving, her many friends will be\ng id to know.\nMiss Ophelia Cocr, who is teaching\nu ar Pinkney, spent several days at\nLer home near here last week on ac\nci notol the sickness of her mother,\nrs. Lou Dail.\n.Mr. Jethro Howell and Miss Cora\n\"Pnyne Moore visited Miss Ethel Per\nkins, cer the river, last Saturday af\nown, nmking the trip on horse\nh..jk, which they very much enjoyed.\nOur enterprising and progressive\ni) -iglibor. Mr. G!eo. Becton, is handling\nl it'..-, nuii me-ui in connection wiih his\nitKk oi KtiieraJ lnorchaiidise, which is\n4)iiiit- si convenience to those here who\n!'U) l:eir (irouuct J'or cow teed.\n:r (1 Mrs. Cm WhiUington, of\ncit;.', spent several days in our\neori:iuiiiiity last week, where Mr.\niiUm.ioii is miMresiod in h lumber\nji.i'.i-. i on their larm. They have hosts\nof nit lids here M ho r.re always glad to\nSf- Sl-.em.\nAii.-ss Hazel (Jiawlord went to Kenly\nlist jiiiuru:ty, where she will attend\nlh.d High hchooJ ai that place and be\nU;t? recipient of the kind hospitality\nuad Ciirisiian influence in the home of\nh r uncle and aunt, Rev. and Mrs. A.\nXj. Ormond.\nThe death of Mrs. Annie Jones, relict\ni the late Mr. II. T. Jones, occurred at\nher home here on Saturday night, lol-!\nloiving u stroke of paralysis on Friday, j\nSiie had been in decliniug htalthfor\nseveral years prior to her husband's\nlentli, about a year apo, and for many\nmonths had been u liable te walk. She\nwas a good woman, and bore her trou\nbles and afflictions with christian forti\ntude. She was buried from her home\nSunday atiernoon, the funeral being\"\nattended by a lare crowd, aud the ob\nsequies conducted by the pastor ol the\nBaptist eh.urtb of your city, of which\nshe waa a consistent member. The\nfamily have the sympathy of numerous\nfriends,\nW,had an invitation to participate\nA1?- gide Tyme Fiddlers' Conven\ntion, and\" Would have liked to have\ngone down and done some kind of fid\ndling, on such pieces as \"Nellie Gray,\"\n\"Old Fo.ks at Home,\" \"Annie Laurie,\"\n\"Pomp Longs Cotillion,\" \"Chapel Hill\nSdrnade,\" etc. But the misfortune ol\nimpaired function oi the auditory ap\nperattus, renders \"fiddling\" more or\nless dilliouU. We do not know wheth\ner it would interfere with performing\non the violin or not. This reminds us\nofalriend, who was very much sur\nprised when he asked us to perform on\nthe violin, and we told him we could\nnot do so had never attempted it but\nthat we fiddled a little, sometimes.\nOur valet, Alex Bryan, the old ante\nbellum darkey who has been in the\nfamily ever since we can remember,\nhas been off duty the past week with\ngrip, and as plentiful labor is the un\nknown quality in this section, we have\nbeen man-of-all-work and \"Johnnie\non the spot,\" when the many chores\naround the farm needed doing. There\nis no little degree of satisfaction and\nconsolation in being independent to\nlabor, and able and willing to do the\nmany little things around the home,\nwhen it is impossible to get labor lor\nlove or money. But we are enjoying\nthe work, it is good for one's health,\nand no matter how long it lasts we\nwill trv to be thankful and remain\n\"colen and serene.\"\nMr. Cal Richardson, who lives near\nthe junction, had a thrilling exper\nience one day last week with a runa\nway horse. On his way to your city,\nin a one-horse wagon, the horse took\niright near Mr. Ben Sasser's, and Mr.\nRichardson losing control of him, he\nran to chapel church, nearly two miles,\nwhere he reined him against a tree and\nsioppea mm. VVnen He passed our\nshanty, as Toby says, he was \"carry\ning it in,\" and it looked as if he was\njust being held steady enough to do\nhis best running. We are glad Mr.\nRichardson escaped injury, and ad\nmire his pluck in sticking to the lines,\nwhen he could have turned him loose,\n\"and gotten out of the rear end of the\nwagon. He met several vehicles in the\nroad but they all side-tracked, seeing\nhe had the right of way.\nThe Leap Year Party which held the\nboards at Oak Glen last Wednesday\nnight,conducted by Misses Cora Payne\nMoore and Effie Swinson, was a de\ncided success, so far as enjoyment was\nconcerned. The gentlemen guests were\nsupplied with hearts and mittens, and\nas the question was proposed, a pre\nsentation of either, decided whether it\nwas accepted, or rejected. There was\nconsiderable amusement afforded, and\nMiss Mamie Johnson was presented\nwith the prize, a manicure set, for hay\ning secured the greatest number ol\nhearts, and Miss Lizzie Wiggs, the\nbooby, an egg beater, for receiving the\nmost mittens. 'Prof. E. C. Byerly pre\nsented the prizes in a most appropriate\nand well fitting speech, which was en\njoyed by all present. Near the \"wee\nsma\" hours the crowd dispersed, leav\ning Oak Glen to its usual quietude,\nwith the rememberance of an eveninir\nmost pleasantly enjoyed.\nAnother Word\nof Warning\nII\nWIT RESTORED TO HIM.\nElopement from Southern Part Of\nCity Settled Yesterday\nWilmington Star.\nMr. W.\"H. H. Todd, 1006 South Sec\nond Street, who charged in a warrant\ns worn out before Justice Furlon Sun\nday night that his wife eloped with a\ncarpenter named Strange Pridgen and\n-who was engaged with the police Fri\nday and Saturday in a fruitless search\nfor the couple in this city, received in\nformation yesterday morning by long\ndistance telephone from Kinston that\nthe man had been arrested there with\nthe wife and little (daughter whom she\ntook with her when she disappeared\nfrom home, leaving a note with the\nhusband, Friday night. Mr. Todd\nwent to Goldsboro yesterday morning\nand met an officer from Kinston with\nPridgen, but says that he found aster\nreaching there that his wife did not\nrun away with the man and upon his\nreturn to this city last night with\nPridgen. his wife and daughter, the\nwarapt was withdrawn and Pridgen\nwas given his liberty.\nMr. Todd asks that the statement be\nmade that Pridgen is not of the \"un\nknow tongue\" sect as was printed from\ncommon report in these columns Siin-\ndaylmorning.\nThis is the man whopassed through\nGoldsboro yesterday, handcuffed, in\ncharge of an officer on his way to\nWilmington Ed. Argus.\nYour Duty is to be Welt.\nBut you cannot be well if you neglect\ntaking Hood's Sarsaparilla when you know\nyou should take it. Impure blood, poor\nappetite, headache, nervousness, that tired\nreeling by these and other signs your sys\ntcm demands Hood's. Get a bottle today.\nC!CW Of Health \"My blood was very\nfloor. Since taking Hood's Sarsaparilla I\n.itvo more color in my face, sleep and eat\nwll. and work is a pleasure.\" Mrs. A. A.\nHowabd. Taunton, Mass.\nIrt Worst Form \"I had catarrh in the\nmtv&t form and was advised to try Hood's\nS.-irsaparilla. I took seven bottles and am\nnow in srood health. 1 hope everyome who\nf.s?s catarrh will give Hood's a fair trial.\"\nilRS. William Metcalf, Parkerford, Pa.\nAlways Praise \"I first took Hood's Sar\nsaparilla 13 years ago, and always speak in\nfavor of it.\" H. Cowdell, 237 Perry Street,\nloweLl. Mass.\nHood's Sarsaparilla is\" sold everywhere.\nla the usual liquid, or in tablet form called\nr3atabs. 100 Doses One Dollar. Pre-\nJ nsily by C. I. Hood Co., Lowell, Mass.\n1735\n1780\n1816\n1828\n1847\n1856\n1873\n1889\n1902\n\"THIS DAY IN HISTORY.\"\nFebruary 11.\nDaniel Boone, Kentucky pio\nneer, born in Pennsylvania.\nDied in Missouri, Sept, 26,1820.\nThe British, under Sir Henry\nClinton, began their attack on\nCharleston, S. C.\nFort Boyer, Mobile, surren\ndered to the British.\nDe Witt Clinton, \"father of the\nErie canal,\" died at Albany.\nBorn March 2, 1769.\nThomas Alva Edison, inventor,\nborn at Milan, Ohio.\nPresident ordered dispersion\nof armed invaders of Kansas.\nAbdication of King Amadeus\nof Spain and proclamation of a\nrepublic.\nConstitution of Japan pro\nclaimed. Anglo-Japanese alliance announced.\nRETURNING PROSPERITY.\nThousands of idle Workmen Are\nBeing Reinstated In Old Positions.\n(Special to The Argus.)\nNew York, Feb. 11. Dispatches\nfrom all the large manufacturing cen\nters throughout the country\" today tell\nof thousands of workmen, who have\nbeen laid off for months, returning to\nwork.\nThe return of prosperity is in full\nswing again and all feel sure of better\ntimes.\nNEW CORRENCY BILL.\n(Special to The Aeous.)\n.Washington, Feb. 10. Chairman\nAldrich of the Senate Finance Com\nmittee is today delivering the principal\nspeech of the session in the Senate on\nthe proposed new currency law bill.\nHis utterances are of much interest\nat this time on this subject.\n'Buying a piano is lamely a matter of confi\ndence, because very lew people can .judge of its\nmerits. The smooth-tonguedjsolicitor persuades\nmany, even against their judgment, and when too\nlate, the deception is discovered.\nWhen you buy from any but a well known\nmanufacturer, you are apt to get a niano of low\ngrade, probably a \"Stencil Piano\" that cannot\nstand tne tests of time and use.\nWhen you buy a STIEFF PlAJMO, you get\nthe one that has been wrell and widely known for\nmore than a half century, and run no risk?\nWrite for catalogue.\nESS\nf\" L. C. Steele, Manager,\nrTGVanbygSt., NORFOLK, VA.\n'Jhe piano with the Sweet Tone\" official Piano Jamestown Exposition.\n(MENTION THIS PAPER WHEN WRITING.)\nf-L P J'' irTYWtmiMifci\nSouthern Standard of Satisfaction\nU\nH0GLESS LARD\n(o\nV V III 1 f I 11 if ic f i II\nhim\nfc-\nr\nijip-A',\nNature made it, and made\nit right, -the just-right cooking-fat\nfor all purposes, -the\neconomical substitute for\nbutter. There's no indigesti\nble hog-fat in it. It's the pride\nof the South, -her leading\nagricultural contribution ta\ninternational food-purity.\n4\n1\nBLOOD FILLED WUH URIC ACID\nRheumatism comes from an excess of uric acid in the blood. This acid\ncirculating through the system acts as an irritant to the different muscles,\nnerves, bones and tissues ot tne body, ana produces tne mnammauon anu\nswelling of the joints and the sharp, cutting pains characteristic of the dis\nease. When the blood is overburdened with uric acid it continually grows\nweaker and more acrid, and poorer in nourishing qualities. Then Rheuma\ntism becomes chronic, and not only a painful, but a formidable and danger\nous disease. Sometimes the heart is attacked, the general health is affected,\nand the oils and fluids which lubricate the muscles and joints are destroyed\nby the acrid matter which the blood is constantly depositing in them the\nmuscles shrink and lose their elasticity, the coating of the joints becomes\nhard and thick, and often the sufferer is left a hopeles3 cripple. S. S. S.\nattacks the disease at its head, goes down into the circulation, and by neutral\nizing and removing the uric acid from the\ncirculation and building up tne win, acrid\nblood, cures Rheumatism permanently.\nS. S.' S. changes the sour, acid-burdened blood\nto a rich, healthy stream which quiets the\nexcited nerves, eases the throbbing, painful\nmuscles and joints, and filters out of the\nsystem the irritating matter wnlch is causing\nthe pain and inflammation. Begin the use of S. S. S. now and get the cause\nout of your blood so that the cold and dampness of Winter will not keep you\nin constant pain and misery. Book on Rheumatism and any medical advice\nfree. THE SWIFT SPECIFIC CO., ATLANTA, GA.\nPURELY VEGETABLE\nIs the joy of the household, for without\nit no happiness can be complete. How\n6weet the picture of mother and babe\nAnerels smile at and commend tho\nN thoughts and aspirations of the mother\nbending over the cradle. The ordeal through\nwhich the exp